	.articleContent
		div
			.callout--adviser
				h2 Note for Advisers
				p This page outlines the #[strong current] eligibility for Universal Credit, also known as the ‘gateway conditions’.
				p Eventually, clients in different circumstances will also be able to claim Universal Credit, but at the moment there are restrictions on who can claim while it’s being rolled out.
				p This page will be updated regularly as the eligibility rules change.
			p Universal Credit is a new benefit that you can only get in some parts of the UK.
			p If you’re living in a Universal Credit area, you might need to apply for Universal Credit instead of other existing benefits like Jobseeker's Allowance, Housing Benefit or Tax Credits etc.
			p It’s mainly available to people who are unemployed or earn less than £338 a month - but you can get it in some other circumstances.
			h2.ref-heading#h-get-help
				span.ref-heading__heading Get help
				span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
					a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
			p It can be complicated to work out if you’re eligible just by reading all the small print - the rules are outlined in full below.
			p It might be quicker and easier to talk to an expert so you can explain your personal circumstances. You can do this in a few ways:
			ul
				li call the #[strong Universal Credit helpline] on 0345 600 0723 (Textphone: 0345 600 0743). Calls can cost 9p a minute from a landline, or between 8p and 40p a minute from a mobile (your phone supplier can tell you how much you’ll pay). You can call and ask them to call you back
				li contact your #[a(href="/about-us/how-we-provide-advice/advice/search-for-your-local-citizens-advice/") local Citizens Advice]
			h2.ref-heading#h-who-can-apply-for-universal-credit
				span.ref-heading__heading Who can apply for Universal Credit
				span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
					a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
			h3.ref-heading#h-you-can-currently-only-apply-in-a-universal-credit-area
				span.ref-heading__heading You can currently only apply in a Universal Credit area
				span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
					a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
			p The first thing you should do is see if you live in a Universal Credit area. Follow these steps:
			ol
				li #[a.a-external(href="http://los.direct.gov.uk/default.aspx?type=1&amp;lang=en", rel="external", target="_blank") Find your nearest Jobcentre] if you don’t know it.
				li Check the list of #[a.a-external(href="https://www.gov.uk/jobcentres-where-you-can-claim-universal-credit", rel="external", target="_blank") Jobcentres that accept Universal Credit applications] to find out if your nearest Jobcentre is on the list. Some Jobcentres are only accepting claims from single people - the list will say where.
			p If you can’t apply for Universal Credit, you should look at other benefits - use the Turn2us benefits checker to #[a.a-external(href="http://benefits-calculator.turn2us.org.uk/AboutYou", rel="external", target="_top") see what you can apply for]. Your #[a(href="/about-us/how-we-provide-advice/advice/search-for-your-local-citizens-advice/") local Citizens Advice] can also help you.
			h3.ref-heading#h-if-you-live-in-a-universal-credit-area
				span.ref-heading__heading If you live in a Universal Credit area
				span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
					a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
			p To be eligible for Universal Credit, you must currently:
			ul
				li expect to earn less than £338 (after tax) in the next month
				li be #[span#overlay_button-2 between 18 years old and 60 years and 6 months old]
				li be a British citizen (non-British citizens can #[a(href="/benefits/universal-credit/before-you-apply/eligibility-non-british-citizen/", target="_top") apply in some places])

				li have a National Insurance number
				li have less than £6,000 in savings or other investments - eg shares, or property that you don't live in. This is increased to a £16,000 limit if you live in certain areas of Sutton or Croydon - see below
			p If you live with your partner, you usually both need to be eligible. You'll need to:
			ul
				li live at the same address (you don't have to be married or civil partners to apply)
				li expect to earn less than £541 (after tax) combined in the next month
				li have less than £6,000 in savings or other investments between you. This is increased to a £16,000 limit if you live in certain areas of Sutton or Croydon - see below
			p There are currently very limited circumstances when you can apply as a single person while being part of a couple who is living together. You can read more in #[a(href="/benefits/universal-credit/before-you-apply/how-universal-credit-works-for-couples/") the rules for how Universal Credit works for couples].
			h3.ref-heading#h-the-following-conditions-will-also-apply-unless-you-live-in-sutton-or-croydon-
				span.ref-heading__heading The following conditions will also apply (unless you live in Sutton or Croydon)
				span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
					a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
			.callout--warning
				p There are fewer restrictions on applying if you live in parts of Sutton and Croydon. If you have a postcode beginning with SM5 2**, SM6 7**, SM6 8**, SM6 9** or CR0 4**,  this section does not apply to you. If you live anywhere else in the UK, you'll need to meet the conditions below as well as the conditions already listed.

			p You must have lived in the UK for the last 2 years, and not have been abroad for more than 4 weeks continuously during that time.
			p You #[strong can’t] get Universal Credit if any of the following apply:
			ul
				li you can't work or look for work (eg because of illness or disability)
				li you’re in supported or temporary accommodation
				li you’re a homeowner
				li you’ve applied for a fitness for work note from a doctor
				li you’re pregnant or have given birth within the last 15 weeks
				li you have caring responsibilities, eg for a disabled person
				li you’re self-employed, or expect to earn money from self-employment in the next month
				li you’re a company director or part of a limited liability partnership
				li you’re in education or on a training course of any kind
				li you live in the same household as a member of the regular or reserve forces who’s away on duty
				li you pay child maintenance via the Child Support Agency
				li you’re an approved foster parent (even if you have no foster children)
				li you’re expecting to adopt a child in the next 2 months
				li you’ve adopted a child within the last 12 months
				li you’re homeless
			p If you're not sure whether or not you can apply, contact the Universal Credit helpline or visit your #[a(href="/about-us/how-we-provide-advice/advice/search-for-your-local-citizens-advice/") local Citizens Advice].
			p
				strong Universal Credit helpline
				br
				| Telephone: 0345 600 0723
				br
				| Textphone: 0345 600 0743
				br
				| Monday to Friday, 8am to 6pm
			p Calls to this number can cost up to 9p a minute from a landline, or between 8p and 40p a minute from a mobile (your phone supplier can tell you how much you’ll pay). You can call and ask them to call you back.
			p Your #[a(href="/about-us/how-we-provide-advice/advice/search-for-your-local-citizens-advice/") nearest Citizens Advice] can also help.
			.callout--info
				p If you can’t apply for Universal Credit, you should look at other benefits - use the Turn2us benefits checker to #[a.a-external(href="http://benefits-calculator.turn2us.org.uk/AboutYou", rel="external") see what you can apply for].

			h3.ref-heading#h-if-you-ve-applied-for-other-benefits
				span.ref-heading__heading If you've applied for other benefits
				span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
					a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
			p You can’t get Universal Credit if you've applied for any of the following and you're waiting for a decision:
			ul
				li Jobseeker’s Allowance
				li Employment and Support Allowance
				li Income Support
				li Housing Benefit
				li Child Tax Credit
				li Working Tax Credit
			p You can’t get Universal Credit if you’re appealing against a decision to not give you any of the following:
			ul
				li Jobseeker’s Allowance
				li Employment and Support Allowance
				li Income Support (IS)
			p You can’t get Universal Credit if you’re waiting for a revision of a decision (including a 'mandatory reconsideration') to not give you any of the following:
			ul
				li Jobseeker’s Allowance
				li Employment and Support Allowance
				li Income Support
				li Housing Benefit
			p You can’t get Universal Credit if you’re entitled to:
			ul
				li Employment and Support Allowance
				li Income Support
				li Incapacity Benefit
				li Severe Disablement Allowance
				li Disability Living Allowance
				li Personal Independence Payment
			p You might be eligible for other benefits if you’re not eligible for Universal Credit. Use the Turn2us benefits checker to #[a.a-external(href="http://benefits-calculator.turn2us.org.uk/AboutYou", rel="external") see what you can apply for], or contact your #[a(href="/about-us/how-we-provide-advice/advice/search-for-your-local-citizens-advice/") nearest Citizens Advice].
			.callout--related
				h2.ref-heading#h-next-steps
					span.ref-heading__heading Next steps
					span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
						a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
				p #[a(href="/benefits/universal-credit/apply/apply-for-universal-credit/") Apply for Universal Credit].

			.callout--adviser
				h2.ref-heading#h-information-for-advisers
					span.ref-heading__heading Information for advisers
					span.ref-heading__toggle.ref-heading__toggle--off
						a.js-toggle-ref(href="#!") Add reference
				p More detailed guidance on eligibility for Universal Credit can be found in:
				ul
					li the decision makers' guide - chapter C1 on GOV.UK - remember this is guidance for DWP staff and not the defined law
					li the 'Child Poverty Action Group (CPAG) Welfare Benefits and Tax Credits Handbook' for more detailed guidance on eligibility





