				h2.overlay__header 9.2.1.85 Universal Credit - which 16 and 17 year olds can get it?
				p To get UC, you have to meet certain basic conditions of entitlement and in most cases must be aged at least 18. A 16 or 17 year old who meets special conditions is able to claim UC. This page explains those special conditions.

				h3 16 and 17 year olds who can claim Universal Credit

				p You can get UC at age 16 or 17 where you satisfy one of the following conditions:
				ul
					li you have limited capability for work or are waiting for an assessment and have provided medical evidence. More about limited capability for work
					li you have caring responsibilities for a severely disabled person. More about caring responsibilities for a severely disabled person
					li you or your partner are responsible for a child. If your partner is responsible for the child, your partner must meet the basic conditions including being age 18
					li you are pregnant and your baby is due within 11 weeks or was born no more than 15 weeks ago
					li you are without parental support and not looked after by the local authority.
				p However, if you are 16 or 17 and a care leaver you are not eligible for UC unless you have limited capability for work (or are awaiting assessment) or you or your partner are responsible for a child.

				p If you satisfy one of the conditions for getting UC at age 16 or 17 you may not have to meet any work-related requirement.

				p More about work-related requirements.

				p More about which work-related requirements do you have to meet.

				p More about who is in the no work-related requirements group.

				h4 Without parental support

				p Without parental support means that you:
				ul
					li have no parent; or
					li cannot live with your parent because of estrangement. This means you cannot live with your parent because your relationship has broken down emotionally; or
					li cannot live with your parent because your health would be at risk if you lived with them or because they are unable to support you financially because of their physical or mental condition; or
					li you cannot live with your parent because they are in prison; or
					li you cannot live with your parent because they are not allowed to enter Great Britain.
				h3 Claiming Universal Credit if your partner is aged 16 or 17

				p If your partner is aged 16 or 17 and meets the special conditions you can make a joint claim for UC.

				p If your partner is aged 16 or 17 and does not meet the special conditions you can claim as a single person.

				p If you have to claim as a single person your entitlement is based on your circumstances but  your partner’s income and capital are taken into account.

				p More about couples who have to claim UC as a single person.
